description.plain: This song tells a narrative- not always with a clear meaning, but dealing with themes of love, reciprocation, and growing up. Throughout the song, Gish seems to come to an important conclusion, and attempt to share it with others- but to the listener, this conclusion is not necessarily clear. Overall, this song forgoes traditional structure to create an ambiguous, poetic piece of music with clever wordplay and an intriguing message.

annotations: Carrying my zombie arm to the fifteenth grade prom

This lyric is different from the previous version of the song, being “fifteenth grade prom” rather than “fourteenth grade prom.” This suggests that whatever she is struggling with in this song, perhaps romantic feelings for someone or an internal struggle with herself or her life, it has been going on for an entire year and she is sick and tired of it and frustrated with herself for her inability to resolve it or – like the arm – put it down.
’Cause nearly everyone skipped over me

The lyric in this version is slightly different from the one in the original song. It’s changed to this from “Every stupid boy skipped over me.” The change perhaps implies that at least one person hasn’t “skipped over” the artist from her last version of the song, but has actually shown an interest in her. The use of the gender-neutral “everyone” is also a nice change since it implies that her romantic pool doesn’t only include boys, or it may mean she isn’t speaking in a romantic sense, and someone didn’t skip over her platonically.

description.plain: The sin triangle is the father, son, and holy ghost/ id, ego and super ego.  It describes the self being pulled apart by the allure of the id’s power and the super ego’s wisdom, and how it’s like a sickness upon our soul and source of constant suffering as it makes us lost on our path to knowing, and being known by others. But also the reason we can hold two contradictory truths simultaneously and the blessing of the free will to choose pleasure over pain and make friendships as an individual who is by nature, alone and divided.

annotations:
Peacing out at eleven, the
 Friendly girls are trying to comfort me as if
 I’m a depressed chick at a frat party

“Peacing out at eleven” is to say leaving at “the "Eleventh Hour”, meaning, the last possible moment, as if it were being put off or delayed. The “pretty girls trying to comfort me” are represented by 3 women spaced evenly apart around her as she lays in the music video, signifying the 3 fates. (Life, death, rebirth)

I’m certain that I’m gonna die this time
 No doubt is left inside my mind tonight
 So I’m just gonna wait for nausea to set in

This is likely referring to preparation for a psychedelic experience. “Death” here refers to ego death, the experience of the dissolution of the ordinary sense of self on high doses of psychedelics.

The “nausea” is a common side effect felt on the ‘come-up’ to a psychedelic trip for drugs such as LSD, psylocibin, and 2-CB.

Gish has made explicit references to her drug use in other songs, such as Presumably Dead Arm, so this is not a stretch.
[Verse 1]

The track is silent for the first three seconds. This is consistent with a line from the previous track “Bird Tutorial.”

“For the next few seconds, this record will be silent
Then begins your parakeet’s talking lessons”

Two-faced bitches never lie
 And therefore I never lie

two faced bitches, by nature, lie
“two faced bitches never lie” = false
i never lie = false
what i said = false
me = two faced bitch

-From Sidney’s AMA here: https://www.reddit.com/r/indieheads/comments/84i7ow/ama_sidney_gish_here_made_an_album_no_dogs/

Two-faced bitches never lie
 And therefore I never lie

she quotes in a reddit AMA,

“two faced bitches, by nature, lie
"two faced bitches never lie” = false
i never lie = false
what i said = false
me = two faced bitch"

Two-faced bitches never lie
 And therefore I never lie

This line captures a syllogism know as an enthymeme. A syllogism is a statement where a conclusion is drawn from two assumed premises, and an enthymeme is a syllogism where one of the premises is missing.

Here, the missing premise would be “I am a two-faced bitch.” The full statement would be “I am a two-faced bitch, and two-faced bitches never lie, and therefore I never lie.”

This type of reasoning is often taught in Geometry (like concepts of sine triangles) with the Transitive Law, which states a = b and b = c, therefore a = c.

And maybe I wanna see him
 But then again I’m an isolationist

“She puts her noncommittal attitude in geopolitical terms to satirize the benefits of distance” – Nina Corcoran, Pitchfork

Isolationism refers to a nation’s policy of avoiding entanglements with other countries.

A sickness by another name
 Wouldn’t be sweet either but

A barbed allusion to the Bard. The line is a play on the oft-cited Romeo and Juliet balcony scene from Act II, Scene II. Juliet asks her lover:

“What’s in a name?
That which we call a rose
By any other word would smell as sweet”

The line is usually paraphrased as, “A rose by any other name would smell as sweet.”

[Spoken Interlude]
 Let’s see how personality works
 Bill Woodruff here has something on his mind
 He wants something
 In fact—

Both interludes in this song are sampled from this 1951 educational film, titled “Improve Your Personality.” It was published by Coronet Instructional Films, a company that published documentary shorts commonly shown in American public schools between the 1940s and 1980s.

https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=VvFF9NlRlxQ

Diagram this sin triangle
 But the biblical kind and not sine

Sine is a trigonometric function of an angle, often abbreviated as “sin.” Sin is also a word for a transgression against God, hence “the biblical kind.” Since the sine function is defined in terms of triangles, you can understand why “sin triangle” might be misconstrued.

description.plain:
“Impostor Syndrome” is about how Sidney Gish feels as if she isn’t good enough and not worthy of her achievements. She is hyper-aware of herself and knows that she shouldn’t feel so insecure, but she can’t help herself with her imposter syndrome.

Her insecurity and anxiety comes from the overwhelming rise of her music career. Gish has been highly acclaimed over the years with her previous releases including the bandcamp releases since 2015 and the 2016 full-length studio album Ed Buys Houses, getting opportunities to perform at many venues. But being only 20 years old studying at Northeastern University, juggling her music career wasn’t so easy. She told how she experienced anxiety of becoming famous in the 2017 interview with Allston Pudding:

I’ve noticed that I tend to overcompensate for feeling weird, like, my panic response is to be weird as fuck. It used to be being quiet and it still is, but now there’s, like, a threshold where I start being terrifying once I cross. I felt super weird about that for a long time, but [I realized people] just express their anxiety in different ways than me. They don’t just think I’m uncool… well, they probably do, but I’m expressing it through being loud.

“Imposter Syndrome” highlights her trademark lyricism expressing her anxiety becoming an adult and feeling doubts in her accomplishments and anxiety of not having a full roadmap of her life with a sense of humor. The bubbly melody masks the dread of the expressions, but her falsetto voice in the chorus portrays her truer delivery of the lyrics.

annotations: Victor
possibly a continued reference to victor frankenstein. see the previous annotation.
Nobody outs behavioral Frankenstein

“Frankenstein” refers to Victor Frankenstein from the eponymous 1818 novel by Mary Shelley. Frankenstein is the creator of the creature, commonly referred as “the monster,” made with mishmash of body parts of human corpses. After feeling disgusted at himself for building a creature that became lonely and depressed as a result of being treated poorly by anyone it encountered, Frankenstein commits suicide. The novel’s theme revolves around the imperfection in human pursuit of knowledge for the root of human life and purpose.

Sidney feels as if she had artificially built her personality and music that’s a mishmash of traits from her favorite musicians and other influential people in her life. She thinks of herself as both the creator and the creation of Victor. Her “behavioral Frankenstein” alludes to her having feelings akin to Victor’s for building something disgustingly deformed he initially envisioned to be a perfect design of the source of human life. She had stitched together traits of people she admired and aspired to be, ending up insecure that she became unoriginal and imperfect.

In the 2017 interview with Boston Globe, she mentions drawing inspiration from “musicians like Vampire Weekend, Of Montreal, and Regina Spektor” and adapting their idiosyncratic lyricism and innovative instrumentation to her own music. She was a member of choir in middle and high school, and she was part of the a cappella scene in college, where she also learned to beatbox. She additionally learned to play the piano, the ukulele, and the guitar.

I’ll get an idea for a melody and then lyrical ideas, and I have to put them together on my own. I wish I got into a state of flow where both are happening at the same time; that would be really cool, but that never happens. […] I really liked doing theater in middle school, because I got to pretend to be somebody else, and whenever I was playing a character, I was fine. But to do singer-songwriter stuff on stage didn’t really come naturally.

Despite the fact that all of her inspirations and skills contributed to her success in building her own style of music, Sidney described her process of writing her own songs and creating melodies as “Frankensteining” in the interview.

Unfortunately, I am
 My own dog, my own fur companion
 My own old lady on a forum

In this verse, Sidney introduces her self-perceived awkwardness by comparing herself to two awkward beings. If you’ve ever seen an old lady try to use social media, you’ll notice that they aren’t quite as tech savvy as younger people. On forums, older people often write very formally, and to the more digitally fluent ~youth~ it sounds pretty awkward. And then, of course, dogs are cute and great, but they don’t exactly have human-like behavior or social skills. She also isn’t very happy about all this, which is why she starts her thought with “unfortunately”.

But we can get more psychological here, and with a song called Impostor Syndrome, why wouldn’t we?

When Sidney says “I am / My own dog, my own fur companion / My own old lady…” she creates a dichotomy of her self- basically meaning she separates herself into multiple parts in her mind. It normally wouldn’t make sense for one thing to be the “dog” of itself, but because of this separation, she is saying that one aspect of herself is the “dog” of another aspect of herself. The more conscious part, the owner of the metaphorical dog and old lady, seems to be Sid’s ego, the organized and rational part of the self in Freud’s psychoanalytic theory. The old lady and the dog seem to represent Sid’s id, which is the instinctual and uncoordinated counterpart to the ego.
Not K through 8, nor K dash 9

Throughout the song Gish makes comparisons between dogs and humans. “K through 8” refers to Kindergarten through Grade 8, and K–8 schools which enroll students for that amount of time. “K dash 9” or K-9 is the name given to police dog units, hence “canine.”
These sweet instincts ruin my life

This line is also in the chorus of “I Eat Salads Now”. Here, Sidney’s instincts are to questions her competency, which is a bit of a foil to the other song in the album. In “I Eat Salads Now,” Sidney comes off much more confident with declarative assertive statements like “I’m a businessman, I don’t waste time on any shit”, and even from the title “I Eat Salads Now!” In “Imposter Syndrome,” the atmosphere changes to be more critical unsure of her insecurities.

annotations:
I’m a businessman, I don’t waste time on any shit
 (Don’t waste time, don’t waste time on shit, what?)

Sidney graduated Northeastern University with a music industry major in 2020. In Northeastern University, students are required to work co-ops or semester-long internships in order to graduate. Sidney chose to spend the time to work at professional musical labels.

She originally planned to go into sociology or songwriting for her major, but on the Common Application for Northeastern, she applied as a music business major. She talked about how she wanted to focus on business than strict conservatory training in the 2017 interview article by The Huntington News. She said:

I was going to major in songwriting, but then I’d just be going around trying to get approval from all of my songwriting professors. I’d probably still be doing that if I had gone to Berklee [College of Music].

At the time she wrote and released No Dogs Allowed, she was still a student while being a successful musician, managing her own music career by self-releasing her albums. She took no break to “waste time on any shit,” and didn’t want to be bothered by other people while studying in university and managing her music career that would slow her down. Calling herself a “businessman” rather than a “businesswoman,” “businessperson,” or “musician,” she is depicting herself in the stereotypical caricature of a Wall Street office worker who calls themselves “self-made man.”

(Bitch, I’m wasted) Bitch, I’m wasted
 (Just kidding, I’m high) Just kidding, I’m high

Sidney repeats the same line from the earlier chorus. However, the line weighs a heavier meaning as the song progresses.

She uses the word “wasted” as a way to express how she feels “washed up already” at the age of 20. Her bandcamp music career had taken off since 2015 with songs she had written since 2011, at which she was 14 years old. Her 2016 debut full-length studio album Ed Buys Houses brought her up to a great deal of fame that prompted her to tour for an entire year taking a break from college. Still, being 20 years old in 2017 when she released No Dogs Allowed, juggling her music career with being in college was no cakewalk. She was hanging out with different groups of people, one from her college and the other from the music industry. At such age when she’s still trying to grasp a sense of her own identity, she feels as if she’s outgrown her youth. But at the same time, she’d just like to take a break and be “high,” as in stoned smoking weed.

In this chorus, “I’m high” has a double meaning in contrast to the first chorus. She is alluding to her “high” success in her music career. While she tells how dreadful the business aspect of being in the music industry is to be in, she tries to laugh it off by sounding sarcastic when she says she’s “wasted” in regards to her life’s progress.

The multitude of conflicting feelings makes her overwhelmed, but she tries to keep on moving on to the next thing. The way she repeats this line shows her growth.
Bitch, I’m wasted, just kidding, I’m high

Sidney no longer drinks alcohol like she used to like when she was possibly underage or partying in college to fit in. She compares being “wasted” to being “high,” as in smoking marijuana instead. The title “I Eat Salads Now” holds different interpretations, one of which is that she now smokes “green,” slang for marijuana. Sidney is growing out of her earlier teenage years when she was trying to find her identity, and now knows what she wants, finding her own people instead of drinking to a stupor trying to socialize.

Followed by this line’s laughed off tone, she later uses the word “wasted” again in a different meaning in the same repeated line.

These sweet instincts ruin my life
 There’s no progress, just good times

This line is also in the chorus of “Imposter Syndrome”. The narrator in this song comes off with a bit more confidence, although there still seems to be some tension under this hook. While good times are rolling, the narrator reflects that “there’s no progress” and their current lifestyle may actually be detrimental to them in the long term. This foreshadows Imposter Syndrome, where they admit that they have no idea whats going on.
I’m 20, washed up already
These lines interpolate Frankie Cosmos' “I’m 20”

annotations:
But I’ll mispronounce and mis-accent for infinity
 There isn’t much that you could do to stop me

Sidney feels she keeps making mistakes she should be avoiding and learning from (like a mispronunciation, which is used as a metaphor here), and no matter how hard she tries, or other people try for her, she’ll keep making the same mistakes over and over to the point where she doesn’t want to try anymore.

If I’d a known I’d mess up this many times
 Then I’d shut up for the rest of my life

Self-doubt and “Shutting up” is a theme in Gish’s music. In her other song “Homecoming Serf”, she states:

“It’s no one’s fault but mine
That I shut up
For all of eighteen years”

And Greek goddesses aren’t what
 You grab when leaving home

This is a pun on the previous line – purse-a-phone is a mispronunciation of the greek goddess' name, but also a phone and purse might be what you grab before leaving your house – Persephone was also kidnapped by hades, according to the legend, which further feeds into this theme of taking things away from home.
I pray Greek gods don’t see me
Persephone herself is a greek goddess, but she is referring to her family here, her mother and father/father in law/uncle and maybe even her uncle on both sides/husband Hades.
Please don’t visit me

Please don’t visit refers back to the line “I pray Greek gods don’t see me butchering names and not believing.” She doesn’t want Persephone to visit and see Sidney butchering her name. However, Persephone not visiting would also delay the coming of spring and summer. By wishing for Persephone to not see her mispronunciation, Sidney inadvertently wishes for an indefinite winter. Although she only wants her mistakes to not be seen, her small wish creates a much greater consequence.
Like Hades’ lair
Hades is Persephone’s husband, his lair probably refers to the underworld, where Persephone spends half the year in greek mythology.
By the name Purse-a-phone

“Purse-a-phone” is a common mispronunciation for “Persephone” (“purr-SEH-fuh-nee”), the daughter of Greek goddess Demeter. Gish uses this mispronunciation to exemplify her lack of concern for the expectations that are placed on her by society.
Persephone
Persephone is the Greek goddess of vegetation, especially grain, and the wife of Hades, with whom she rules the Underworld
Six pomegranate seeds, winter in Greece

In Greek myth, while captive in the underworld, Persephone ate six pomegranate seeds. Because she had eaten food in the underworld, even after she was set free she was required to spend part of the year there, namely the winter.
